==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|homogeneus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ὁμογενής||of the same race, family or kind|lang=grc}}, from  {{term|ὁμός||same|tr=homos|lang=grc}} + {{term|γένος|tr=genos||kind|lang=grc}}. Compare {{term|homo-||same|lang=en}} and {{term|-ous|lang=en}}, adjectival suffix.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/hɒ.məˈdʒiː.nɪəs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/hɑməˈdʒiniəs/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Of the same kind; [[alike]], [[similar]].
# Having the same [[composition]] throughout; of [[uniform]] make-up.
#* '''1946''', {{w|Bertrand Russell}}, ''History of Western Philosophy'', I.25:
#*: Their citizens were not of '''homogenous''' origin, but were from all parts of Greece.
# {{context|chemistry}} in the same [[state of matter]].
# {{context|mathematics}} Of which the properties of a smaller set apply to the whole; [[scalable]].
#: ''The function ''f(x,y)=x<sup>2</sup>+y<sup>2</sup>'' is homogeneous of degree 2 because ''f(''α''x,''α''y)=''α''<sup>2</sup>f(x,y)''.''

